        <h1>Credit card glossary</h1>
        <p>
            This is a collection of the financial jargon you will have to be familiar with to efficiently use your credit cards in Malaysia. Looking for a more general
            Q&amp;A? Head over to our <a href="http://www.moneyhero.com.hk/credit-card/faq">general credit cards FAQ</a> page.
        </p>
        <div id="accordion" class="glossary">


            <h4>
                Air miles
            </h4>
            <p>
                Air miles is a reward points system that allows you to exchange your accumulated miles for free flights and other related discounts.
            </p>
            <h4>
                Annual Fee
            </h4>
            <p>
                A fee charged once a year for having a credit card. Many standard credit cards waive the annual fee for the first year, while some even offer a RM0 fee for
                life.
            </p>
            <h4>
                Annual Percentage Rate (APR)
            </h4>
            <p>
                APR is the total cost of the credit card, shown as a percentage. APR includes fees and interest. It shows you how much the interest rate will be on an
                annual basis. APR makes it convenient for applicants to compare the different credit cards in Malaysia, although you should bear in mind that the interest
                rate offered to you will depend on your individual credit score.
            </p>
            <h4>
                Automatic Payment
            </h4>
            <p>
                Automatic payment is a service that allows regular withdrawals from your savings or current account to be made in order to pay bills or other debts
                automatically.
            </p>
            <h4>
                Available Credit
            </h4>
            <p>
                This refers to the amount of unused credit available. In essence, your credit limit minus any outstanding balance.
            </p>
            <h4>
                Average Daily Balance
            </h4>
            <p>
                Average daily balance is calculated by adding all daily balances together and then dividing by the number of days in the billing period.
            </p>
            <h4>
                Bad Credit
            </h4>
            <p>
                Bad credit is used to refer to a low credit score. Making late payments or defaulting, going over your limit, and filing for bankruptcy are some of the
                factors that cause bad credit.
            </p>
            <h4>
                Balance Transfer
            </h4>
            <p>
                In general financial terms, balance transfer is the act of transferring credit from one account to another. For credit card transactions, balance transfer
                can be a form of debt consolidation and management. It allows you to transfer the outstanding of one account to another. You may opt to do this if you want
                to enjoy the benefits of a lower interest rate. A balance transfer fee is applicable, even if you have a 0% balance transfer interest rate.
            </p>
            <h4>
                Balance Transfer Fee
            </h4>
            <p>
                This fee is charged when you transfer balance from one account to another. It is usually a certain percentage of the amount transferred.
            </p>
            <h4>
                Card Issuer
            </h4>
            <p>
                Card issuer refers to the provider of the credit card. A card issuer can be a financial institution, bank, or union.
            </p>
            <h4>
                Cash Advance
            </h4>
            <p>
                You may withdraw money from your card issuer’s ATM using your credit card; this service is known as a cash advance or a cash withdrawal. You will be
                charged a cash advance fee and cash advance interest for using this service.
            </p>
            <h4>
                Cash Advance Fee
            </h4>
            <p>
                This is a fee charged for the cash withdrawal service. The cash advance fee is usually a certain percentage of the amount withdrawn.
            </p>
            <h4>
                Cashback
            </h4>
            <p>
                Many credit cards have a cashback feature, which allows you to get back a certain percentage of your spending. This feature is useful if you always use
                your credit card to pay for groceries and bills.
            </p>
            <h4>
                Credit Bureau
            </h4>
            <p>
                A credit bureau is an agency that keeps a record of your spending and other related financial information. These records are used to calculate your credit
                score. The main credit bureau in Malaysia is part of Bank Negara Malaysia. You can request a copy of your credit report here (external link to
                <a href="http://creditbureau.bnm.gov.my/index.php?ch=5&amp;pg=7&amp;ac=10&amp;lang=en">
                    http://creditbureau.bnm.gov.my/index.php?ch=5&amp;pg=7&amp;ac=10&amp;lang=en
                </a>
                ).
            </p>
            <h4>
                Credit Card Insurance
            </h4>
            <p>
                This is a form of insurance that helps you pay your credit card bill should you fail to do so due to accident or death.
            </p>
            <h4>
                Charge Card
            </h4>
            <p>
                This is a form of payment that requires full repayment by the due date each month. There is no pre-set spending limit for charge cards.
            </p>
            <h4>
                Credit Card
            </h4>
            <p>
                Credit cards are a form of payment which allow you to pay on credit. Credit cards come in the form of a plastic card with an encoded magnetic strip on the
                back. They are accepted worldwide.
            </p>
            <h4>
                Credit History
            </h4>
            <p>
                Your credit history is a record of your credit; this includes loans, credit cards, overdrafts, etc. It also shows a record of your repayment.
            </p>
            <h4>
                Credit Limit
            </h4>
            <p>
                This is also known as credit line. It is the maximum amount that you may charge to your credit card. Your credit limit depends on the type of credit card
                you have and on your credit score. You will be charged an over limit fee if you exceed your credit limit.
            </p>
            <h4>
                Credit Monitoring Service
            </h4>
            <p>
                A credit monitoring service can assist you in keeping an eye on your credit card account. It will alert you if it notices any suspicious transactions on
                your credit card.
            </p>
            <h4>
                Credit Score:
            </h4>
            <p>
                Your credit score represents your ‘creditworthiness’ and is used by lenders to determine whether to approve your credit card or not. Maintaining a good
                credit record is important as it will help you get better interest rates and deals on your credit cards. To find out how to check and improve your credit
                rating, read our guide on everything you need to know about your credit score.
            </p>
            <h4>
                Credit Scoring
            </h4>
            <p>
                When deciding whether to approve a loan or not, lenders will assess your application using the details you provided, as well as your credit history and
                other information provided by the Credit Reference Agency. This process is known as credit scoring, or credit rating. This means that maintaining a good
                credit record is important. Paying off existing debts on time will help to improve your credit score.
            </p>
            <h4>
                Credit Verification Code (CVC)
            </h4>
            <p>
                CVC, also known as Card Security Code (CSC) is a security feature on your credit card. It is either a three- or four-digit number written on the back or
                the front of your Visa / Mastercard or AmEx credit card respectively, depending on the type of card you have.
            </p>
            <h4>
                Debit Card
            </h4>
            <p>
                A debit card is a form of payment that allows you to pay for products and services using money from your account. This form of payment does not involve
                credit.
            </p>
            <h4>
                Debt Consolidation
            </h4>
            <p>
                Debt consolidation is when you combine several debts into one. This is often done to enjoy a lower interest rate and to make paying off your debt more
                convenient.
            </p>
            <h4>
                Finance Charges
            </h4>
            <p>
                Interest and fees charged to your credit card are known as finance charges.
            </p>
            <h4>
                Fixed Rate
            </h4>
            <p>
                An annual percentage rate (APR) that does not change over time.
            </p>
            <h4>
                Floor Limit
            </h4>
            <p>
                When a single transaction exceeds the floor limit, authorisation is required. This helps to protect you against credit card fraud.
            </p>
            <h4>
                Fraudulent Transaction
            </h4>
            <p>
                Fraudulent transactions are unauthorised transactions on your credit card. Be sure to alert your card issuer as soon as you notice any fraudulent
                transactions made using your card.
            </p>
            <h4>
                Grace Period
            </h4>
            <p>
                The grace period refers to a fixed period of time after you receive your credit card bill. During the grace period, you can pay off what you owe without
                being charged interest.
            </p>
            <h4>
                Interest Rate
            </h4>
            <p>
                Interest rate is the percentage of your balance that is charged for using a credit service. Interest rate is usually given as a yearly rate.
            </p>
            <h4>
                Interest-Free Period
            </h4>
            <p>
                During this time, interest will not be charged for purchases made using your credit card. This is between the date of purchase and when payment is due.
            </p>
            <h4>
                Introductory Rate
            </h4>
            <p>
                The annual percentage rate charged during your credit card’s introductory period. Your interest rate will change after the introductory period ends.
            </p>
            <h4>
                Late-Payment Fee
            </h4>
            <p>
                This is a charge imposed when you fail to pay by the due date.
            </p>
            <h4>
                MasterCard
            </h4>
            <p>
                MasterCard is a global card payment brand. MasterCard credit cards are accepted worldwide.
            </p>
            <h4>
                Minimum Interest
            </h4>
            <p>
                This refers to the minimum amount you will be charged for interest.
            </p>
            <h4>
                Minimum Monthly Payment
            </h4>
            <p>
                This is the lowest amount of money you need to pay each month for your credit card.
            </p>
            <h4>
                Outstanding Balance
            </h4>
            <p>
                This is the amount you owe. This balance will be used to calculate your monthly interest.
            </p>
            <h4>
                Over Limit Fee
            </h4>
            <p>
                The over limit fee is charged if you exceed your credit limit.
            </p>
            <h4>
                Payment Due Date
            </h4>
            <p>
                This is the date when you are supposed to pay at least your minimum monthly payment. If you miss the payment due date, you will be charged a late payment
                fee.
            </p>
            <h4>
                Personal Identification Number (PIN)
            </h4>
            <p>
                Your PIN is the security number for your credit card. You need your PIN to withdraw money from ATMs using your credit card.
            </p>
            <h4>
                Prime Rate
            </h4>
            <p>
                Prime rate is the interest rate card issuers charge their credit worthy customers.
            </p>
            <h4>
                Principal Cardholder
            </h4>
            <p>
                The principal cardholder is the main cardholder. The card is registered under the principal cardholder’s name and the principal cardholder is liable for
                the spending made by supplementary cardholders linked to the account.
            </p>
            <h4>
                Purchase
            </h4>
            <p>
                A purchase is when you buy something from a merchant. This includes groceries, shopping, dining, and so on.
            </p>
            <h4>
                Retail Credit Card
            </h4>
            <p>
                This is a credit card associated with a retail store. Usually retail credit cards offer you rewards or discounts for spending in store. Some retail credit
                cards allow you to use reward points you have accumulated at other places too.
            </p>
            <h4>
                Secured Credit Card
            </h4>
            <p>
                A secured credit card requires you to put down a deposit before you can use the credit card. You may apply for a secured credit card if you would like to
                build or improve your credit score.
            </p>
            <h4>
                Service Tax
            </h4>
            <p>
                Service tax is imposed by the Ministry of Finance, and it is the same for all credit cards in Malaysia. For principal cardholders, it is RM50 per card per
                year, while supplementary cardholders pay RM25 per card per year.
            </p>
            <h4>
                Supplementary Cardholder
            </h4>
            <p>
                A supplementary cardholder is a third party nominated by the principal cardholder. Supplementary cardholders get the use of an additional credit card
                issued under the account of principal cardholder.
            </p>
            <h4>
                Statement
            </h4>
            <p>
                You will receive a statement from your credit card issuer each month. This details your credit card activities over the past month. It will also indicate
                the payment due date.
            </p>
            <h4>
                Unsecured Credit Card
            </h4>
            <p>
                This refers to credit cards that do not require a security deposit. Most ‘normal’ credit cards offered in Malaysia fall under this category.
            </p>
            <h4>
                Variable-rate APR
            </h4>
            <p>
                An APR which changes in congruence with other factors, such as the instance prime rate. This is the opposite of fixed rate.
            </p>
            <h4>
                Visa
            </h4>
            <p>
                Visa is one of the biggest credit card brands in the world, and its cards are accepted worldwide.
            </p>
            <br>
            <p>
                Got a good grasp of credit card jargon now? Learn more from our <a href="http://www.moneyhero.com.hk/credit-card/guide">comprehensive credit cards guide</a>
                to be a financially savvy credit card expert.
            </p>
